A case-control design is a study in which two groups of people are being compared. In a typical case control study, one group of participants is selected from the general population, and a second group is chosen from people who have a specific health condition, such as a disease.

A case-control design is a type of observational study. In a typical case control study, two groups of people are studied: cases and controls. Cases are people who have a disease or condition, and the controls are healthy people.

A case-control design is a study design where cases are people who have a disease and controls are healthy people. In a typical case control study, the researcher will compare the amount of a substance (such as lead) in the blood of people with the disease to the same substance in people without the condition.

A case-control design is used when researchers want to determine if a certain exposure is associated with a particular disease. In a typical case control study, researchers will identify two groups of people: those who have the disease and those that do not. They will then ask people in the first group about their exposure history. This is known as the case group. People in both groups will be asked about other factors such as lifestyle, diet, and genetics that could be related to the development of the condition. The control group will not have any known exposure to a disease-causing agent.
